large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When John \"Telynwr\" ap Gruffudd was born in 1408, in Margam, Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Gruffudd ap Cynhaethwy, was -166 and his mother, Mrs. Gruffudd ap Cynhaethwy, was -170. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Mrs. John Telynwr ap Gruffudd."},"et":{"1408–":"1408–Surnud","1408–Male":"1408–Surnud","1601–Male":"1601–Surnud","1412–Female":"1412–Surnud","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1429–Male":"1429–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1432–Male":"1432–Surnud","1575–Male":"1575–Surnud","1579–Female":"1579–Surnud","1426":"1426","1579":"1579","1425":"1425","1601":"1601","about 1429":"umbes 1429","1412":"1412","about 1426